      <hedline>
        <hl1>Bush vs. Gore, Round 1: Now the People Debate; All Debate, All the Time?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ray LeFebvre letter disputes Oct 3 Op-Ed article by FCC chairman, William E Kennard, which criticized NBC and Fox Network for refusing to air first presidential debate</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Fox and NBC Renege on a Debt,'' by William E. Kennard (Op-Ed, Oct. 3):</p>
        <p>The purpose of the debates is to let the people see and hear the candidates, so that they can make a choice.  The purpose of having more than one television network is so that people can make a choice.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Fox and NBC Renege on a Debt,'' by William E. Kennard (Op-Ed, Oct. 3):</p>
        <p>The purpose of the debates is to let the people see and hear the candidates, so that they can make a choice.  The purpose of having more than one television network is so that people can make a choice.</p>
        <p>Where is the choice if the same thing is on four networks at the same time? If I want to watch the debate, I will watch the network that is broadcasting it. I have that choice.</p>
        <p>RAY LEFEBVRE  Brooklyn, Oct. 4, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
